1.See what distribution of gdp_per_capita / suicides_percentage is across countries.

suicide_df <- suicide_df %>% rename('gdp_per_capita' = 'gdp_per_capita ($)' , 'suicide/100k' = 'suicides/100k pop') %>%
  select("country","year","sex","age","suicide/100k","gdp_per_capita", "suicides_no", "population") 
head(suicide_df)
## # A tibble: 6 x 8
##   country  year sex   age   `suicide/100k` gdp_per_capita suicides_no
##   <chr>   <dbl> <chr> <chr>          <dbl>          <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 Albania  1987 male  15-2           6.71            796          21
## 2 Albania  1987 male  35-5           5.19            796          16
## 3 Albania  1987 fema 15-2           4.83            796          14
## 4 Albania  1987 male  75+            4.59            796           1
## 5 Albania  1987 male  25-3           3.28            796           9
## 6 Albania  1987 fema 75+            2.81            796           1
## #  with 1 more variable: population <dbl>
suicide_by_year_df <- suicide_df %>% 
  group_by(country, year) %>%
  summarize(suicide_no = sum(suicides_no), population = sum(population), gdp_per_capita = sum(gdp_per_capita)/n()) %>%
  ungroup()
head(suicide_by_year_df)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   country  year suicide_no population gdp_per_capita
##   <chr>   <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Albania  1987         73    2709600            796
## 2 Albania  1988         63    2764300            769
## 3 Albania  1989         68    2803100            833
## 4 Albania  1992         47    2822500            251
## 5 Albania  1993         73    2807300            437
## 6 Albania  1994         50    2849300            697
suicide_by_year_df <- suicide_by_year_df %>% 
  mutate(suicide_percentage = suicide_no / population * 100, suicide_percent_per_100gdp = suicide_percentage/gdp_per_capita * 100) 
head(suicide_by_year_df)
## # A tibble: 6 x 7

Just by the spread, youd think wed have a roughly inverse relationship between the percent of a population committing suicide and the gdp_per_capita, but the linear regression line reveals that there might be a slightly positive linear relationship between the two or maybe no relationship at all.

suicide_by_year_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = gdp_per_capita, y = suicide_percentage)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm)

Heres a better look at the distribution of gdp_per_capita we saw in the last plot.

suicide_by_year_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = gdp_per_capita)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Another look

suicide_by_year_df %>% ggplot(aes(y = gdp_per_capita)) + geom_boxplot()

suicide_by_year_df %>% filter(year %in% c("1990","1995", "2000", "2010","2015")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=gdp_per_capita, y=suicide_percentage)) +
  facet_grid("year") +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method=lm)

Now gdp_per_capita across time

suicide_by_year_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = year, y = gdp_per_capita)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm)

And suicide rates across time. This contradicts the claim that theres a relationship between gdp per capita and suicide rates, since, on average, gdp steadily climbed while suicide percentage stayed constant.

suicide_by_year_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = year, y = suicide_percentage)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm)

suicide_by_year_df %>% ggplot(aes(x = year, y = suicide_percent_per_100gdp)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm)
